      <section>
      Get a quick start with Google <a href="https://developers.google.com/fusiontables/docs/v2/sql-reference">fusion tables sql</a>. You need <a href="https://support.google.com/fusiontables">some fusion tables you own</a> (and/or some <a href="https://research.google.com/tables?hl=en&ei=xYqhVpuCJsHipQOqzLiIDw&corpus=fusion&q=dog">external table IDs</a>), a <a href="https://console.developers.google.com">google developers project</a>, an <a href="https://console.developers.google.com/apis"> activated fusion tables api</a> and an <a href="https://console.developers.google.com/apis/credentials"><a href="https://console.developers.google.com/apis/credentials">OAuth2 client ID</a></a> for the project. <small>(the OAuth2 client ID must be for application type "other")</small>  
      <p></p>
      <b>Covers: </b> SELECT, CREATE VIEW, UPDATE, DELETE, DESCRIBE and SHOW TABLES
      <br><b>Adds:</b>	ALTER TABLE - RENAME TO and DROP TABLE
      </section>
      <p></p>
     
 <wide_section>
    <p></p>

<p> <img src="ftc.gif" width="750" height="498" alt=""> </p>
        <p></p>
<h3>Known Limitations</h3>
        <ul>
        	 <li>Column ids can be used in queries, but they are not covered by syntax highlighting</li>
        	 <li>If a table has an alias, the alias must always be preceded by the keyword "AS"</li>
        	 <li>Handling of huge amounts of data isn't the goal of the implementation. On the other hand, it may take you as far as the computer's memory allows it to.</li>
        </ul>

      </wide_section>


